HEADWORD: Purtenance
<hw>Pur"te*nance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. fr.
<ets>appurtenance</ets>.]</ety> <def>That which pertains or belongs to
something; esp., the heard, liver, and lungs of an animal.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧ The <xex>purtenaunces</xex> of
purgatory.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Roast [it] with fire, his head with his legs, and with the
<qex>purtenance</qex> [<it>Rev. Ver.</it>, inwards] thereof.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. xii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purulency</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Purulence</ent>⟦br⟧
